Project Outline: Census Data¶

This is the collection, cleaning, and merging section of the final capstone project "To Everything There is a Season : Using Weather Data and Demographic Information in the Predictive Modeling of Crimes in Dallas, Texas' by Ashley Steele.

2. Creating Sub-dataframes and Preparing for Merging¶

Return to outline

For this section of the project we are going to look at two data profiles (DP03- employment data & DP05-demographic data) from the American Communities Survey (ACS) from 2015 to 2018. We are igoring any time frames for census data that are not within the scope of our Dallas P.D. calls. The original non-API datasets can be found here

To help organize our data for merging we will use the following naming conventions for our final, pre-merging datasets:

  • 2015 = df1
  • 2016 = df2
  • 2017 = df3
  • 2018 = df4

# Creating a resuable function to help us clean up all column names 
def clean_columns(name):
    old_column_names= list(name.columns)
    new_column_names= [str(x).lower().replace(' ', '_').replace(';', '_').replace('-', '').replace('__', '_') for x in list(name.columns)]
    return name.rename(columns= dict(zip(old_column_names, new_column_names)), inplace = True)
In [8]:

Excellent! Let's move on to our next step: figuring out the relationship between zip codes within Dallas City limits and U.S. Census tracts!

3. Zip Code/County/Tract Relationships¶

Return to outline

Census information is organized by several different geographic levels, such as state, county, zip code, and tract. In order to get our census information into a format we can use with our other datasets we must associate our original census data (sorted by tract) with the correct zip codes for the city of Dallas. Let's do that below!

This all looks super great.... but we are still missing one year's worth of data (2018). Unfortunately, the U.S. Census Bureau switched data systems for 2018 data and we must struggle with their confusing API to get the same information we obtained for prior years. Let's work on our API call below!

5. Trying to Make Sense of the API Call Structure for U.S. Census¶

Return to outline

5.1: Practicing Our API Call Format¶

Return to outline

Note: Since our API key is individualized and secret our final project upload to Github will not have the key proivded.

Ok, we're getting a little closer! What we have above is one row of data from the Data profiles section of the ACS 1year report from 2018. The DP02__## is only one of the variables. This query selected the name of the state, the info for just that variable and the code for the state. Let's see if we can go down more levels with the same variable.

5.2: Setting up Our Variables¶

Return to outline

Let's make a comprehensive list of what variables we actually want to call from the census API:

DP03:

  • 0001E- number of individuals 16 & over (pop able to work)
  • 0001PE- % of pop working able
  • 0004PE - % of pop employed
  • 0005PE- % of pop unemployed
  • 0062E- Mean household income
  • 0118PE- % of families in poverty last 12 months
  • 0127PE- % of individuals in poverty last 12 months

DP05:

  • 0001E- total pop
  • 0002 E& PE- males
  • 0003 E & PE- females
  • 0018E- median age in years
  • 0019PE- Under 18
  • 0020PE- 16 & over
  • 0021PE- 18 & over
  • 00022PE - 21 & over
  • 0023PE - 62 & older
  • 0024PE - 65 and older
  • 0037 PE- 1 race white
  • 0038 PE- Black
  • 0039PE- Native
  • 0044PE- Asian
  • 0071PE - Hispanic

# Getting DP03 data from 2018
for x in dp03_features:
    sample = requests.get('https://api.census.gov/data/2018/acs/acs1/profile?get=NAME,{}&for=county:113&in=state:48&key={}'.format(x, key))
    my_list= ast.literal_eval(sample.text)
    d[my_list[0][1]]= float(my_list[1][1])
    sleep(1)

For the next subset of information I had to do a little more digging to help figure out just how much of the total population the city of Dallas accounts for in Dallas County numbers. I found out, by looking up the county numbers for 2017, that the city itself accounts for 81% of the total county numbers. We will use that percentage below!
